WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.280
Speaking of differences between R and Python, I seem to remember, and you can correct me

00:00:07.280 --> 00:00:15.680
if I'm wrong about this, but I feel like you have a famous tweet from years ago where you

00:00:15.680 --> 00:00:22.280
say, somebody says something like, and it must have been a famous poster themself that

00:00:22.280 --> 00:00:27.200
you responded to, and I can't remember, it might have been like Wes McKinney or somebody

00:00:27.200 --> 00:00:33.520
like that, saying that one of the advantages of Python is that it's faster than R, and

00:00:33.520 --> 00:00:38.520
then you have this super famous reply of, what is that, and I will make it faster.

00:00:38.520 --> 00:00:40.520
Do you know what I'm talking about?

00:00:40.520 --> 00:00:44.520
I don't, but I know I've said things like that in the past.

00:00:44.520 --> 00:00:50.880
No, that's a, it's a, yeah, it is, it's kind of a, it's a misperception, because Python

00:00:50.880 --> 00:00:56.599
isn't actually that fast itself, I mean, whole languages like Julia have come up to be faster

00:00:56.599 --> 00:00:57.599
than Python.

00:00:57.599 --> 00:01:03.799
Yeah, I think, I think one of the reasons, like, you know, often, like, the biggest,

00:01:03.799 --> 00:01:07.959
you know, you have the worst arguments with your family and not with strangers, like,

00:01:07.959 --> 00:01:11.639
with people who are, like, so, like, so similar to you, you tend to have more friction than

00:01:11.639 --> 00:01:15.879
the people who are, like, really different, I think, because R and Python are actually

00:01:15.879 --> 00:01:19.720
really close together in the spectrum of programming languages.

00:01:19.720 --> 00:01:24.320
It's so easy to see, like, all of the, like, the little things that look weird to you,

00:01:24.320 --> 00:01:28.360
as opposed to looking at some programming language that's miles away, and it just looks,

00:01:28.360 --> 00:01:32.360
you know, totally different, you can't, I just think that, I don't know, I think there's

00:01:32.360 --> 00:01:37.919
a, there's something to that, it's, it's because we're close, you can see these, like, little

00:01:37.919 --> 00:01:38.919
noises.

00:01:38.919 --> 00:01:39.919
You're right.

00:01:39.919 --> 00:01:42.919
Certainly, like, when I see things in Python that people are like, wow, that's really cool,

00:01:42.919 --> 00:01:46.239
I'm like, challenge accepted, I will make that better now.

00:01:46.239 --> 00:01:47.239
Nice.

00:01:47.239 --> 00:01:51.839
One of my favorite things that you can do really well, thanks to the dplyr library that

00:01:51.839 --> 00:01:54.959
you led development of, is piping.

00:01:54.959 --> 00:02:02.000
And so you can extremely easily have functions pass into, I mean, just like if people are

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:07.160
familiar with Unix programming, pipes there, where you have output from one function goes

00:02:07.160 --> 00:02:13.000
the input to the next function, and prior to me discovering dplyr, which was probably

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:18.279
around 2010, if that makes sense.

00:02:18.279 --> 00:02:25.880
Prior to that, I would have so many variables in my workspace, it was just such a pain to

00:02:25.880 --> 00:02:29.320
keep them all straight, and you just end up in these weird situations where, like, should

00:02:29.320 --> 00:02:33.520
I be investing time thinking about the name of this intermediate variable, am I going

00:02:33.520 --> 00:02:41.360
to use this later, or should I just name it, like, intermediate variable 15, and have really

00:02:41.360 --> 00:02:42.360
ugly code.

00:02:42.360 --> 00:02:49.360
And so piping gets rid of all that, where you can read the flows like a sentence.

00:02:49.360 --> 00:02:53.559
You're like, okay, this preprocessing step happens, then this next, and you can just

00:02:53.559 --> 00:02:56.559
see it so easily, it makes it so elegant to read.

00:02:56.559 --> 00:03:02.559
Do you think we'll get to a point where, and I have used some kinds of piping attempts

00:03:02.559 --> 00:03:07.800
in Python, but my experience of that has never been, and I guess it's been a few years since

00:03:07.800 --> 00:03:13.880
I've tried, but it seems like it's never been as smooth or as easy as with R, and maybe

00:03:13.880 --> 00:03:17.960
that's related to what you were talking about earlier with data visualization.

00:03:17.960 --> 00:03:26.160
So one, kind of the native equivalent of piping in Python is like method chaining, you know,

00:03:26.160 --> 00:03:32.320
like if you're using pandas, you do something dot something, dot something, dot something.

00:03:32.320 --> 00:03:38.080
But the big difference between method chaining and the pipe is in method chaining, all of

00:03:38.080 --> 00:03:42.919
those methods have to come from the same class, they have to live in the same library, the

00:03:42.919 --> 00:03:43.919
same package.

00:03:43.919 --> 00:03:49.880
Whereas with piping, they can come from any package.

00:03:49.880 --> 00:03:54.880
And I think the thing that's really interesting about that is that that has meant, like, Python

00:03:54.880 --> 00:04:03.199
has tended to have, like, these fewer, bigger packages, like pandas and scikit-learn, matplotlib,

00:04:03.199 --> 00:04:06.800
like kind of everything, in order to work with method chaining, like everything has

00:04:06.800 --> 00:04:12.759
to be glommed into this one giant package, where with R, you know, because you can combine

00:04:12.759 --> 00:04:17.440
things from different packages, like the equivalent of pandas is kind of like dplyr and tidyr and

00:04:17.440 --> 00:04:23.040
readr and like a bunch of other things, like with, it's way easier to add extensions to

00:04:23.040 --> 00:04:27.320
ggplot2 than matplotlib that work exactly the same way, because you don't have this,

00:04:27.320 --> 00:04:29.799
you can just combine them from different pieces.

00:04:29.799 --> 00:04:34.040
So I think that's just one of these, like, sort of interesting, like, subtle differences

00:04:34.040 --> 00:04:40.359
in language design, that leads to, you know, fairly big impacts on the user experience

00:04:40.359 --> 00:04:44.679
and kind of almost even how the community has to work together and form.

